@@ -139,3 +139,62 @@ Required redaction metadata fields:
 - `redactionClasses`: coarse classes such as `credential`,
   `authorization-header`, `private-key`, `project-path`, `gameplay-sensitive`,
   or `oversize-text`.
+
+Redaction metadata semantics:
+
+- `policyVersion` identifies the producer policy that classified and rewrote
+  sensitive data. It is safe to return through JSONL, CLI, API, and context
+  output, and should change only when the policy contract changes.
+- `applied` is `true` when any top-level field, metadata value, payload value,
+  or generated summary was replaced, truncated, or path-sanitized. Clean events
+  still include `redactionMetadata` with `applied: false`, `redactedCount: 0`,
+  and empty arrays so readers do not need to infer missing policy state.
+- `redactedCount` counts redaction operations, not unique fields. A field that
+  contains both a bearer token and an oversize text truncation may increment the
+  count twice while appearing once in `redactedFields`.
+- `redactedFields` contains sanitized field paths where redaction occurred. It
+  must never contain raw token values, raw credential key names, raw absolute
+  project paths, raw player identifiers, or other sensitive gameplay data.
+- `redactionClasses` contains coarse content classes, not values or regex
+  captures. Classes are intended for audit, filtering, and tests without
+  leaking the original content.
+
+Field path conventions:
+
+| Example | Meaning |
+| :--- | :--- |
+| `message` | Top-level event field was redacted. |
+| `summary` | Compact AI summary was redacted or truncated. |
+| `target` | Target object, asset, scene, or entity reference was redacted. |
+| `metadata.<sensitive-key>` | A metadata entry had a sensitive key name. The original key is intentionally suppressed. |
+| `metadata.note` | Non-sensitive metadata key `note` had a sensitive value. |
+| `payload.attributes.<sensitive-key>` | A payload attribute had a sensitive key name. |
+| `payload.attributes.playerId` | Non-sensitive payload key `playerId` had a sensitive or gameplay-private value. |
+
+Redaction class semantics:
+
+| Class | Use |
+| :--- | :--- |
+| `credential` | API keys, tokens, passwords, secret assignments, bearer tokens, or credential-like key/value pairs. |
+| `authorization-header` | HTTP authorization headers where the header shape may remain but the credential value is replaced. |
+| `private-key` | PEM or private-key blocks. |
+| `project-path` | Absolute or user-identifying Unity project paths when the output surface should not expose them. |
+| `gameplay-sensitive` | Player identifiers, save data, telemetry payloads, coordinates, inventory, health, economy, or other gameplay/private play-session details that should not be exposed raw. |
+| `oversize-text` | Text shortened by the maximum length policy before persistence or output. |
+
+Reader and producer safety rules:
+
+- Redaction runs before JSONL persistence, HTTP/API responses, WebSocket
+  broadcasts, and AI context generation. Output redaction is still required
+  because older or externally written JSONL files may predate the current
+  policy.
+- CLI/API readers must whitelist only `policyVersion`, `applied`,
+  `redactedCount`, `redactedFields`, and `redactionClasses` from
+  `redactionMetadata`; unknown fields are ignored rather than forwarded.
+- Producers should prefer the narrowest stable field path they can name. If a
+  raw field name is itself sensitive, use `<sensitive-key>` instead.
+- Metadata must describe what class of content was changed, never the original
+  value, secret suffix, path segment, player id, or regex match.
+- If malformed input includes sensitive data inside `redactionMetadata` itself,
+  readers must redact it before returning the object and must not preserve
+  unknown metadata fields.
